SVM & LR Classification

Eyob Gebremariam, Edgar Johnson and Christopher Krug

Assignment research question, prediction¶

For this exercise were are exploring whether the 2014 school data provides evidence about anecdotal claims that schools with a higher diversity of students, i.e., a mix of white, Black, Hispanic, Native American, Asian, tend to have higher attrition rates than schools who are less diverse. Therefore, we will be classifying/identifying schools that may be at more risk of losing experienced teachers.

To explore this research question, we will use teacher experince as a surrogate variable, i.e., schools that have lower values for teacher experience will be interpreted as having higher attrition rates. Addtionally, we will create a bivariate value from the teacher experience attribute.

NOTE: Given the results of lab assingment one, we will perform a principle component analysis (PCA) on the demographic variables. The results of that assignment indicated strong evidence of multicollinearity and this dimension reduction technique may provide more accurate logistic regression predictions.

SVM and Logistic Regression Modeling links to ansers:

  • [50 points] Create a logistic regression model and a support vector machine model for the classification task involved with your dataset. Assess how well each model performs (use 80/20 training/testing split for your data). Adjust parameters of the models to make them more accurate. If your dataset size requires the use of stochastic gradient descent, then linear kernel only is fine to use.
  • [10 points] Discuss the advantages of each model for each classification task. Does one type of model offer superior performance over another in terms of prediction accuracy? In terms of training time or efficiency? Explain in detail.
  • [30 points] Use the weights from logistic regression to interpret the importance of different features for each classification task. Explain your interpretation in detail. Why do you think some variables are more important?
  • [10 points] Look at the chosen support vectors for the classification task. Do these provide any insight into the data? Explain.

def importExcelFiles(dictionary,years,files,directory,sheetKeyword):
    count = 0
    for year in years:
        yearData = str(year)
        fileName = files[count]
        dataFrameName = sheetKeyword+yearData
        pathToFile = os.path.join(directory,fileName)
        sheetNames = pd.ExcelFile(pathToFile).sheet_names
        for sheetName in sheetNames:
            if sheetKeyword in sheetName:
                #Use print to provide user feedback
                print (fileName+" is now '"+dataFrameName+"'")
                try: 
                    dictionary[dataFrameName]=pd.read_excel(pathToFile,sheetname=sheetName,header=None)
                    ## Having an error with 2005
                except:
                    pass
        count = count+1

def selectSchoolRecords(dataFrame,startRow,endRow):
    schoolRecords = dataFrame[startRow:endRow]
    schoolRecords = schoolRecords.reset_index(drop=True)
    return schoolRecords

Data Understanding¶

[10 points] Describe the meaning and type of data (scale, values, etc.) for each attribute in the data file

The 2014 data contains 207 attributes representing 1,767 records. For this assignment we will examine the following 60 of those attributes.

  • recordNumber (integer): An incrementing count of each school record in the 2014 data.
  • schoolID (string): A unique identifier for a school.
  • countyNumber (int): An integer representing the 77 counties in Oklahoma.
  • districtID (category): A string identifier for a district.
  • siteID (category): An identifier for a school.
  • schoolType (category): A categorical integer value indicated the template of the school.
  • template (category): A categorical value indicated the school type.
  • county (category): A string value indicating the county where the school is located.
  • district (category): The district associated with a school record.
  • school (category): A school's name.
  • lowGrade (category): The lowest grade level provided at a school.
  • highGrade (category): The highes grade level provided at a school.
  • gradeSpan (category): Grade levels provided at a school.
  • address1 (string): A school's mailing address.
  • address2 (string): A school's city, state and postal code.
  • telephone (string): A school's telephone.
  • release (category): A binary categorical variable: yes || no.
  • whiteOther_School (float/ratio): The percentage of school's total enrollment whose ethnicity is white or other.
  • black_School (float/ratio): The percentage of a school's total enrollment whose ethnicity is Black.
  • asian_School (float/ratio): The percentage of a school's total enrollment whose ethnicity is Asian.
  • hispanic_School (float/ratio): The percentage of a school's total enrollment whose ethnicity is Hispanic.
  • nativeAmerican_School (float/ratio): The percentage of a school's total enrollment whose ethnicity is Native American.
  • whiteOther_District (float/ratio): The percentage of district's total enrollment whose ethnicity is white or other.
  • black_District (float/ratio): The percentage of a district's total enrollment whose ethnicity is Black.
  • asian_District (float/ratio): The percentage of a district's total enrollment whose ethnicity is Asian.
  • hispanic_District (float/ratio): The percentage of a district's total enrollment whose ethnicity is Hispanic.
  • nativeAmerican_District (float/ratio): The percentage of a district's total enrollment whose ethnicity is Native American.
  • averagePropertyValuePerADM_District (float/ratio): The average property value in a district based on district enrollment.
  • freeReducedLunch_School (float/ratio): Percentage of a school's student enrollment eligible for free or reduced lunches.
  • freeReducedLunch_District (float/ratio): Percentage of a district's student enrollment eligible for free or reduced lunches.
  • population_District (integer/ratio): Population count of those living within district boundaries. Information from the U.S. Census American Community Survey (2008-2012)
  • averageHouseholdIncome_District (float/ratio): Average household income of those living within district boundaries. Information from the U.S. Census American Community Survey (2008-2012)
  • unemploymentRate_District (float/ratio): Unemployment rate (percentage) of those living with district boundaries. Information from the U.S. Census American Community Survey (2008-2012)
  • povertyRate_District (float/ratio): Poverty rate (percentage) of those living with district boundaries. Information from the U.S. Census American Community Survey (2008-2012)
  • singleParentFamilies_District (float/ratio): Single-parent families (percentage) of those living with district boundaries. Information from the U.S. Census American Community Survey (2008-2012)
  • educationalAttainment_collegeAndAbove_District (float/ratio): Percentage of adults (Age 25+) within district boundaries who have a college degree or taken graduate course work. Information from the U.S. Census American Community Survey (2008-2012)
  • educationalAttainment_highSchoolNoCollegeDegree_District (float/ratio): Percentage of adults (Age 25+) within district boundaries who graduated from high school and have no college degree. Information from the U.S. Census American Community Survey (2008-2012)
  • educationalAttainment_lessThan12thGrade_District (float/ratio): Percentage of adults (Age 25+) within district boundaries who have less than 12th grade education. Information from the U.S. Census American Community Survey (2008-2012)
  • fallEnrollment_School (float/ratio): Number of students enrolled in the school during the fall.
  • fallEnrollment_District (float/ratio): Number of students enrolled in the district during the fall.
  • nonSpecialEdTeacherFTE_School (float/ratio): Number of full-time classroom teachers (FTE) at the school who are not special education teachers.
  • nonSpecialEdTeacherFTE_District (float/ratio): Number of full-time classroom teachers (FTE) at the district who are not special education teachers.
  • averageSalaryTeachers_School (float/ratio): Average salary of teachers at the school.
  • averageSalaryTeachers_District (float/ratio): Average salary of teachers at the district.
  • advancedDegreeTeachers_School (float/ratio): Percentage of teachers at the school who have advanced degrees, i.e., graduate degrees.
  • advancedDegreeTeachers_District (float/ratio): Percentage of teachers at the district who have advanced degrees, i.e., graduate degrees.
  • yearsExperienceTeachers_School (float/ratio): Average years of experience among teachers at the school.
  • yearsExperienceTeachers_District (float/ratio): Average years of experience among teachers at the district.
  • studentsInSpecialEd_School (float/ratio): Percentage of students at the school who are in special education.
  • studentsInSpecialEd_District (float/ratio): Percentage of students at the district who are in special education.
  • studentsInELL_School (float/ratio): Percentage of students at the school who are English language learners.
  • studentsInELL_District (float/ratio): Percentage of students at the district who are English language learners.
  • specialEdTeachersFTE_School (float/ratio): Number of full-time special education teachers at the school.
  • specialEdTeachersFTE_District (float/ratio): Number of full-time special education teachers at the district.
  • counselorsFTE_School (float/ratio): Number of full-time counselors at the school.
  • counselorsFTE_District (float/ratio): Number of full-time counselors at the district.
  • otherProfessionalStaffFTE_School (float/ratio): Number of full-time other professional staff at the school.
  • otherProfessionalStaffFTE_District (float/ratio): Number of full-time other professional staff at the district.
  • administratorsFTE_School (float/ratio): Number of full-time administrators at the school.
  • administratorsFTE_District (float/ratio): Number of full-time administrators at the district.

NOTE: Because of the amount of munging necessary to combine all files, we only examined the 2014 data and a subset of that data's attributes to demonstrate our competency at the assignment's objectives

Selected attributes¶

NOTE: These attributes were selected because they appear in most of the files. Later, we will attempt to munge all the Excel files for analysis. We also only selected school level measures. If we were to add district measures in to our selection, duplicate values would appear. Our goal is first to explore factors at the school level and then proceed to explore the district factors that may influence schools.

Logistic regression¶

"Create a logistic regression model ..."

In [50]:
lr_clf = LogisticRegression(penalty='l2', C=1, class_weight=None)
iter_num=0

logAccScores = []

for iter_num, (train_indices, test_indices) in enumerate(cv_object):
    lr_clf.fit(X[train_indices],y[train_indices])
    y_hat = lr_clf.predict(X[test_indices])
    conf = mt.confusion_matrix(y[test_indices],y_hat)
    #print conf[0,0] # TN
    #print conf[1,0] # FN
    #print conf[0,1] # FP
    #print conf[1,1] # TP
    acc = mt.accuracy_score(y[test_indices],y_hat)
    print ("====Iteration",iter_num+1," ====")
    print ('Accuracy:', acc) # Overall, how often is the classifier correct?
    logAccScores.append(acc)
    print ('Misclassification:', 1-acc)  #Overall, how often is it wrong?
    print ("Specificity:",conf[0,0]/float(conf[0,1]+conf[0,0])) # When it's actually no, how often does it predict no?
    print ("Precision:",conf[1,1]/float(conf[0,1]+conf[1,1])) # When it predicts yes, how often is it correct?
    print ("Confusion matrix:\n",(conf))   
    print ("\n")
    print ("Average accuracy score:", sum(logAccScores)/len(logAccScores))

Discuss advantages of each model¶

"Discuss the advantages of each model ..."

The average accuracy score among the three shuffles between the logistic regression and support vector models for our features was about the same, i.e., they both tend to range from 58% to 61% accuracy.

Our models' predictions don't indicate that one technique is more advantageous than the other. The prediction acccuracy was similar for both.

The difference may be negligible because:

  • Our question of interest is too focused
  • The demographic variables may not be strong predictors of our target variable
  • We are using so few features to predict our target variable
  • Our data has thousands more instances than attributes
  • etc

Documentation indicates that the data's characteristics/behavior can make one technique more advantageous than the other.

Source: http://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/svm.html

Plotting the regression weights¶

In [71]:
weights = pd.Series(lr_clf.coef_[0],index=df1.columns)
weights.plot(kind='bar')
plt.show()

Importance of weights¶

  • Demo_pc1: The principal component with high whiteOther loading has a highest importance in classifying schools by teachers experience. However, this could simply reflect that there are more white students in Oklahoma's public schools. Adding federal "locale" factors my provide better differentiation among the target factor, i.e., city schools tend to have a more diverse student body than suburb, town and rural schools.

  • Demo_pc2: The principal component with high Native American loading has nearly as high importance in classifying schools by teachers experience. However, this too could simply reflect that there are large numbers of Native American students in Oklahoma's public schools. Again, adding federal "locale" factors may provide better differentiation among the target factor.

  • Demo_pc3: The principal components with low black & and high hispanic loading has the least importance in classifying schools by teacher experience. Again, adding federal "locale" factors my provide better differentiation among the target factor. Anecdotally, Oklahoma City and Tulsathe state's largest city districtshave historically had high attrition rates and severe teacher shortages.

The combination of model predication accuracies and weights suggest that the diversity of a school's student body may be associated with teacher attrition rates; however these features may be confounding other more relevant factors. Identifiying those factors (e.g., teacher pay, locale, i.e., city, suburb, town, rural, student teacher ratio, etc,) may improve the ability to predict/identify schools at risk of higher attrition rates. More research is necessary.
